This was the case of several physicians , even some of them the most eminent , and of several of the most skilful surgeons . 
They endeavoured to do good , and to save the lives of others . 
But we were not to expect that the physicians could stop God's judgements , or prevent a distemper eminently armed from heaven from executing the errand it was sent about . 
Doubtless , the physicians assisted many by their skill , and by their prudence and applications , to the saving of their lives and restoring their health . 
It remains to mention now what public measures were taken by the magistrates for the general safety , and to prevent the spreading of the distemper , when it first broke out . 
But I am now upon the order and regulations they published for the government of infected families . 
About June the Lord Mayor of London and the Court of Aldermen , as I have said , began more particularly to concern themselves for the regulation of the city . 
