As I could not refrain contributing tears to this man's story , so neither could I refrain my charity for his assistance . 
God will never forsake a family that trust in Him as thou dost . 
So I gave him four other shillings , and bid him go lay them on the stone and call his wife . 
I have not words to express the poor man's thankfulness , neither could he express it himself but by tears running down his face . 
I then asked the poor man if the distemper had not reached to Greenwich . 
I asked him then how it came to pass that those people who had so shut themselves up in the ships had not laid in sufficient stores of all things necessary . 
I asked him if there was any more ships that had separated themselves as those had done . 
I asked him if the distemper had not reached them . 
He told me , if I would assure him on the word of a Christian and of an honest man that I had not the distemper , he would . 
And so the distemper was brought insensibly among them . 
And here I cannot but take notice that the strange temper of the people of London at that time contributed extremely to their own destruction . 
The plague began , as I have observed , at the other end of the town , namely , in Long Acre , Drury Lane , c . 
, and came on towards the city very gradually and slowly . 
Others argued it , because it was in its extreamest violence in Westminster and the parish of St Giles and St Andrew , c . 
, and began to abate again before it came among them which was true indeed , in part . 
But they paid for it afterwards , as I shall observe by and by . 
Indeed , the distress of the people at this seafaring end of the town was very deplorable , and deserved the greatest commiseration . 
This , I say , took away all compassion self preservation , indeed , appeared here to be the first law . 
For the children ran away from their parents as they languished in the utmost distress . 
It is not , indeed , to be wondered at for the danger of immediate death to ourselves took away all bowels of love , all concern for one another . 
Some were delivered and spoiled by the rashness and ignorance of those who pretended to lay them . 
Sometimes the mother has died of the plague , and the infant , it may be , half born , or born but not parted from the mother . 
Some died in the very pains of their travail , and not delivered at all and so many were the cases of this kind that it is hard to judge of them . 
